Jon,

The Amateur Radio Relay League -- well an experimental group -- wants
to create a packet radio network for things like BBS. The intent is to
base the names of the "hosts" on their call letters and other parameters.
There is some confusion about how names relate to addresses and there is
a tendency in part of the groups to have roputing information embedded
in the name. Anyhow, the current names being discussed look something like

	&lt;call letter name&gt;.AMPR.US

Of course, this implies a central administrative authority called
AMPR.US that registers names. The problem however is that they have
taken the view that delegation is not neccessary because of the current
small number of people involved and that hosts will only exist inside
of AMPRNET or outside of it. You can't have a FOO.CS.CMU.EDU inside of
AMPRNET and you can't have the net grow too much (which I forsee as
definitely happening). 

I was hoping the discussion of true personal machines not part of any
organization would resolve the problem.  So far this has not happen and the
current CCITT stuff fails terribly given that AMPRNET members are hams and
basically are on the move by definition....so forcing geographical names like
city and street into the name breaks down.

The question also exists why we don't have names like FOO.CS.CMU.EDU.US?

Looking for answers and still defining the questions,
-Rudy

